// =====================================================================
// 1. About this report
// =====================================================================
= About this report

This document evaluates the gabion gossip protocol under a battery of
scenarios chosen to mirror the methodologies of the gossip literature
— Demers et al. on anti-entropy and rumour-mongering, Karp et al. on
the @math.Theta @math.log #h(0pt) N round complexity of randomised
rumour spreading, Birman et al. on Bimodal Multicast under packet
loss, Das et al. on SWIM's constant per-node load, and Van Renesse et
al. on Astrolabe-style aggregation latency.

Every measurement in this report comes from the *simulated network*
(the in-process #raw("SimRouter") + #raw("SimTransport") defined in
#raw("crates/gabion/src/gossip/sim.rs")) running under virtual time
(#raw("tokio::time::pause()") + a #raw("TokioClock") anchored at
#raw("t = 0")). Datagrams are delivered through #raw("mpsc") channels,
so scenarios are deterministic and run at sub-realtime speed. No
results in this report were collected over real UDP. A real-network
mode for cross-validation is a planned addition to the harness.

== What is measured

#set par(first-line-indent: 0em)
- *Convergence:* virtual milliseconds (and equivalent gossip rounds)
  between the first write and the first sample at which every node's
  aggregate-store total equals the ground-truth total.
- *Per-node bandwidth:* bytes #math.div node #math.div second at
  steady state, captured by the #raw("CountingTransport") wrapper that
  meters every #raw("try_send_to") and #raw("recv_from").
- *Loss tolerance:* convergence under i.i.d. per-link drop probability
  (#raw("LinkPolicy::DropProb"), deterministic per-link splitmix).
- *Partition + heal:* time-to-reconverge from the moment a network
  cut is healed (the SWIM-style failure-recovery metric).
- *Steady-state staleness:* p50 / p95 per-hit lag between when ground
  truth first reached a level and when each node first matched it.

== What is not measured

- Membership / failure detection. Gabion delegates this to Kubernetes
  via the #raw("EndpointSlice") watcher; the gossip protocol assumes
  every advertised peer is alive until removed.
- Real-network UDP characteristics (kernel buffer pressure, queueing
  delay, MTU fragmentation). The #raw("UdpTransport") is realtime, so
  it is exercised by the smoke tests, not by this harness.
- Churn (joins and leaves over time). The peer set is fixed for each
  scenario. Implementing #raw("PeerDiscovery") as a sim type with
  scriptable membership events is the natural next addition.

// =====================================================================
// 2. Methodology
// =====================================================================
= Methodology

== Per-node setup
Each node owns one #raw("GossipRuntime") parametrised by the
scenario's fanout and tick interval. Its outbound transport is a
#raw("CountingTransport") wrapping #raw("SimTransport"); its
downstream aggregate store is the
#raw("BenchAggregateStore<u32>")
defined in the bench crate (a #raw("HashMap<(rule_fp, key, bucket),
u64>") with the same shape as the server's #raw("DashMapStore") but
single-threaded). The CRDT cell store, peer-frontier table, and
dirty rings come from the production library unchanged.

== Per-tick driving
The runner advances virtual time in #raw("sample_interval")-sized
windows. For each window it:

#set par(first-line-indent: 0em)
+ Applies any scheduled network change whose #raw("at") falls in
  #math.lr.openbracket #raw("elapsed") , #raw("elapsed + sample") #math.lr.closebracket.
+ Issues the workload's writes for the window via
  #raw("GossipClient::record"). The runtime applies each hit locally
  before acking, so #raw("ground_truth") is incremented after the ack.
+ Steps virtual time forward in #raw("tick_interval") chunks, yielding
  between steps so the runtime's #raw("tokio::select!") arm fires
  once per tick and emits one gossip frame per fanout peer.
+ Samples every node's aggregate-store total and counter values.

== Loss model
The simulator's link policy is one of #raw("Pass"), #raw("Block"),
#raw("DropFirst { count }"), or #raw("DropProb { p }"). The bench
harness uses #raw("DropProb") for the loss suite — a deterministic
per-link splitmix PRNG decides each packet's fate independently with
probability #raw("p"). Same seed, same drop pattern across re-runs.

== Implementation
The bench is its own crate, #raw("gossip-bench"), at the workspace
level. The CLI binary runs single scenarios (#raw("run")) or JSONL
batches (#raw("batch")); the Python harness in
#raw("bench/plot.py") generates the matrices and runs them; the
renderer in #raw("bench/render.py") emits the SVGs and the Typst data
fragment this document consumes; and Typst compiles the final PDF.

// =====================================================================
// 3. Convergence
// =====================================================================
= Convergence

The Demers / Karp result is that random push-pull rumour spreading
informs every node in #math.Theta(log_2 N) rounds with high
probability, and that O(N log log N) total messages are necessary and
sufficient for any address-oblivious algorithm. Gabion is push-only
but uses #emph[peer-frontier dedup] — the sender consults each
peer's recorded sequence-number frontier before composing a frame —
so it is not address-oblivious, and the asymptote is allowed to dip
below #math.log_2 N.

#figure-svg(
  "/target/gossip-bench/figures/convergence.svg",
  [Left: rounds to converge for a single write, faceted by fanout
   #math.italic[f]. The dotted reference is the address-oblivious
   #math.log_2 #h(0pt) N push lower bound. At #math.italic[f] = 3,
   gabion's production default, the empirical curve sits at or below
   the bound for every N ≥ 16. Right: steady-state per-node
   bandwidth, including the repair-lane heartbeat. The cost is roughly
   linear in fanout but essentially flat in N — the SWIM "constant
   per-node load as the cluster grows" property.],
)

#v(0.5em)

#table(
  columns: (auto, ..(convergence_fanouts.map(_ => auto))),
  align: (right, ..(convergence_fanouts.map(_ => right))),
  stroke: 0.3pt + sub-color,
  inset: 4pt,
  table.header(
    [#text(style: "italic")[N]],
    ..convergence_fanouts.map(f => [#text(style: "italic")[f = #f]]),
  ),
  ..convergence_rows.flatten().map(cell => [#cell]),
)

#v(0.5em)

#par(first-line-indent: 0em)[
  *Reading.* The #math.italic[f] = 3 column tracks #math.log_2 N at
  N = 8 (3 rounds vs 3) and beats it from N = 16 onward (2 vs 4,
  3 vs 5, 5 vs 6). The peer-frontier dedup amounts to per-receiver
  knowledge at the sender, so dropping below the address-oblivious
  bound is consistent with Karp's analysis, not in conflict with it.
]

